1
00:01:29,905 --> 00:01:31,343
Thank you, madame.

2
00:01:33,809 --> 00:01:35,129
Good morning, monsieur.

3
00:01:35,279 --> 00:01:36,324
- Some nice fresh...

4
00:01:36,359 --> 00:01:37,911
- There it is.
- I need some onions.

5
00:01:38,259 --> 00:01:40,606
- Delivered this morning.
Pick them out yourself.

6
00:01:40,641 --> 00:01:41,656
- How are the peaches?

7
00:01:41,666 --> 00:01:43,873
- Eh, the peaches?
Wonderful.

8
00:01:43,908 --> 00:01:45,624
I ate one this morning,
and I never tasted...

9
00:01:45,659 --> 00:01:47,082
- Uh, can I help you?
- Merci.

10
00:01:47,941 --> 00:01:48,753
- Please, monsieur,

11
00:01:48,788 --> 00:01:50,758
be careful with the peaches.
- Yes.

12
00:01:51,063 --> 00:01:53,081
There are some
wonderful plums, monsieur.

13
00:01:53,830 --> 00:01:56,253
If you can't use the plums, then...
- Uh..huh.

14
00:01:58,892 --> 00:01:59,887
- One kilo is enough.

15
00:01:59,922 --> 00:02:02,789
- A kilo and a half, monsieur.
Put it on the scale yourself.

16
00:02:02,824 --> 00:02:03,725
- One kilo.

17
00:02:04,105 --> 00:02:05,254
- Monsieur, string beans?

18
00:02:05,625 --> 00:02:07,711
And there's some lovely carrots
fresh this morning.

19
00:02:07,746 --> 00:02:09,797
- We need some butter.
There's a dairy down there.

20
00:02:09,832 --> 00:02:11,143
- Monsieur, my money, please.

21
00:02:11,279 --> 00:02:12,380
Pay for it.

22
00:02:12,843 --> 00:02:14,358
Uh, excuse me.

23
00:02:14,393 --> 00:02:17,386
I'm looking for the shop
of Mr. Godet, the baker.

24
00:02:17,508 --> 00:02:19,502
We just arrived in town.
Ask the woman.

25
00:02:19,753 --> 00:02:22,077
- Fresh this morning.
Taste one.

26
00:02:22,112 --> 00:02:24,401
Excuse me, please.
Number 26.

27
00:02:24,436 --> 00:02:25,539
There, 3 doors down.

28
00:02:25,574 --> 00:02:26,642
- They are sour.

29
00:02:26,730 --> 00:02:29,637
- Uh, monsieur, because you're
a nice gentleman...

30
00:02:29,820 --> 00:02:35,472
- here, monsieur... especially because you
are a nice gentleman...

31
00:03:28,061 --> 00:03:30,369
Oh. Please, monsieur.

32
00:03:30,404 --> 00:03:33,034
I'm looking for Mr. Godet, the baker.

33
00:03:33,069 --> 00:03:35,198
Dead.
Died a month ago.

34
00:03:35,233 --> 00:03:36,175
Oh.

35
00:03:37,448 --> 00:03:38,430
What a pity.

36
00:03:38,465 --> 00:03:39,412
You know him?

37
00:03:40,136 --> 00:03:41,749
No, my father knew him.

38
00:03:41,784 --> 00:03:42,598
Mm-hmm.

39
00:03:42,809 --> 00:03:44,058
And Mr. Godet's wife?

40
00:03:44,093 --> 00:03:47,447
Oh, she took the children
and moved to Marseilles
to her brother.

41
00:03:47,482 --> 00:03:50,801
Tell your father
that the brother's name
is Pastin in Marseilles.

42
00:03:50,902 --> 00:03:52,701
My...my father's dead.

43
00:03:55,576 --> 00:03:56,335
Oh.

44
00:03:57,614 --> 00:04:01,638
You see, my father told me
that his old friend, Mr. Godet

45
00:04:01,673 --> 00:04:03,028
would someday help me,

46
00:04:03,377 --> 00:04:06,533
So when my father was dead
and there was nobody there,

47
00:04:06,568 --> 00:04:09,380
I wrote him a letter,
to Mr. Godet.

48
00:04:09,415 --> 00:04:11,033
And I packed my things and left.

49
00:04:11,068 --> 00:04:14,285
And I thought Mr. Godet would
be expecting me.

50
00:04:15,030 --> 00:04:15,744
Oh.

51
00:04:17,060 --> 00:04:17,892
I see.

52
00:04:18,758 --> 00:04:21,072
You, uh...have no family?

53
00:04:23,608 --> 00:04:24,832
Where will you go?

54
00:04:26,478 --> 00:04:27,787
You have any money?

55
00:04:27,822 --> 00:04:31,978
Well, I thought Mr. Godet
would let me work for him

56
00:04:32,013 --> 00:04:34,220
in his bakery, perhaps.

57
00:04:35,425 --> 00:04:37,090
I'm very strong, you know?

58
00:04:37,125 --> 00:04:38,303
I'm a hard worker.

59
00:04:38,338 --> 00:04:41,136
I can work very hard
without getting a bit tired.

60
00:04:41,470 --> 00:04:41,941
Hmm.

61
00:04:43,923 --> 00:04:44,718
Come in.

62
00:04:45,755 --> 00:04:47,205
Come in. Come in.
Come in.

63
00:04:49,651 --> 00:04:50,406
Have you eaten?

64
00:04:51,694 --> 00:04:52,974
Not...not today,

65
00:04:53,327 --> 00:04:54,193
Hmm.

66
00:04:54,499 --> 00:04:55,770
Perhaps a little bread?

67
00:04:55,771 --> 00:04:57,007
Oh.

68
00:04:58,770 --> 00:04:59,400
Come on.

69
00:05:00,089 --> 00:05:01,299
A little cheese, maybe, huh?

70
00:05:01,475 --> 00:05:02,204
Thank you.

71
00:05:02,239 --> 00:05:04,797
And, uh...a little wine.

72
00:05:04,832 --> 00:05:05,640
Oh, thank you.

73
00:05:05,675 --> 00:05:06,413
Thank you.

74
00:05:06,448 --> 00:05:07,682
In here. In here.

75
00:05:07,717 --> 00:05:08,917
That's it. Ha ha.

76
00:05:09,842 --> 00:05:12,495
Now, perhaps you
will work for me, eh?

77
00:05:12,509 --> 00:05:15,284
Of course, you understand
I can't pay you while you learn,

78
00:05:15,319 --> 00:05:19,788
but you'll have a nice bed to sleep in
and a stove to cook a little supper,

79
00:05:20,628 --> 00:05:26,678
and in the morning, you will open the shop
and sell a few buttons and pins and, uh...

80
00:05:28,329 --> 00:05:29,941
be my little helper, huh?

81
00:05:31,384 --> 00:05:32,057
Huh?

82
00:05:33,609 --> 00:05:36,241
Hmm. I'm going in here.

83
00:05:36,546 --> 00:05:38,997
Paul, will you get me a bottle
of pinot in the wine shop?

84
00:05:40,621 --> 00:05:43,055
[  Shopkeeper  ]
I'm not going to hurt you.

85
00:05:43,090 --> 00:05:43,905
[  Lili  ]  I want to go.

86
00:05:43,940 --> 00:05:46,099
- Oh, no. Come here.
- Please, I want to go.

87
00:05:46,134 --> 00:05:48,352
- Please.
- Oh, no, no, no.

88
00:05:48,387 --> 00:05:50,167
- I am not going to hurt you.

89
00:05:50,202 --> 00:05:51,947
- I'm telling you, I want to go.

90
00:05:51,982 --> 00:05:53,281
- I want to go.

91
00:05:53,316 --> 00:05:54,546
- No, wait.

92
00:05:54,581 --> 00:05:55,402
- Don't be afraid.

93
00:05:56,004 --> 00:05:56,891
Oh. Yes, monsieur?

94
00:05:56,926 --> 00:05:58,203
May I be of service, monsieur?

95
00:05:58,238 --> 00:05:59,445
A little trouble with my helper.

96
00:05:59,480 --> 00:06:01,711
Very difficult to find good help
these days.

97
00:06:01,746 --> 00:06:03,779
- They're lazy and stupid.
- And uncooperative.

98
00:06:03,814 --> 00:06:05,509
- How much?
- 90 please, monsieur.

99
00:06:05,544 --> 00:06:06,774
70.
I want half a dozen.

100
00:06:06,809 --> 00:06:08,665
85.
What are you
standing there for?

101
00:06:08,700 --> 00:06:09,275
You can get out.

102
00:06:09,310 --> 00:06:10,355
I take her off the streets,

103
00:06:10,390 --> 00:06:13,240
a girl with no references,
no family, no money,

104
00:06:13,275 --> 00:06:14,472
and...colors, monsieur...

105
00:06:14,507 --> 00:06:16,915
and I give her place to sleep
and food to eat

106
00:06:16,950 --> 00:06:18,854
and a fine opportunity
to learn a trade.

107
00:06:18,889 --> 00:06:19,731
And what happens?

108
00:06:19,766 --> 00:06:20,574
Nothing, I hope.

109
00:06:20,674 --> 00:06:21,433
75.

110
00:06:21,465 --> 00:06:22,419
Uh, 80.

111
00:06:22,470 --> 00:06:25,067
She breaks my pitcher
and eats my food.

112
00:06:25,102 --> 00:06:26,298
- I didn't...

113
00:06:26,333 --> 00:06:27,373
- I didn't eat anything.

114
00:06:27,408 --> 00:06:28,706
- I was going to eat, but he...

115
00:06:28,742 --> 00:06:29,706
You're through.
Good-bye.

116
00:06:29,741 --> 00:06:31,504
What are you waiting for?

117
00:06:31,539 --> 00:06:33,394
But my suitcase in there

118
00:06:33,429 --> 00:06:35,249
and my hat and my purse.

119
00:06:36,816 --> 00:06:39,107
Your face is dirty, little mouse.

120
00:06:40,104 --> 00:06:41,848
There is nothing
to cry about.

121
00:06:42,465 --> 00:06:44,726
You should be happy
to leave this place.

122
00:06:45,116 --> 00:06:45,980
It smells.

123
00:06:46,590 --> 00:06:48,310
Does he owe you
any wages?

124
00:06:48,345 --> 00:06:49,440
- Wages?
For what?

125
00:06:49,475 --> 00:06:51,006
She should pay me
for the food she ate.

126
00:06:51,675 --> 00:06:52,355
Ah?

127
00:06:52,390 --> 00:06:56,371
My word of honor, monsieur,
I didn't eat a bite. Not a bite.

128
00:06:56,406 --> 00:06:57,503
All right, all right, look...

129
00:06:58,602 --> 00:06:59,799
Hup!
See?

130
00:06:59,834 --> 00:07:01,376
It's right behind your ear.

131
00:07:01,624 --> 00:07:02,706
No, this one.

132
00:07:04,167 --> 00:07:04,879
See?

133
00:07:06,553 --> 00:07:08,022
It's a trick?

134
00:07:08,224 --> 00:07:09,391
Now, how did you know?

135
00:07:11,627 --> 00:07:13,535
Everything is all right now,
hmm?

136
00:07:14,952 --> 00:07:15,865
What's your name?

137
00:07:17,170 --> 00:07:17,856
Marc.

138
00:07:18,384 --> 00:07:19,207
Marcus.

139
00:07:19,772 --> 00:07:21,796
Marcus the magnificent.

140
00:07:23,232 --> 00:07:24,116
It suits you.

141
00:07:24,151 --> 00:07:25,000
- Enough!

142
00:07:25,331 --> 00:07:26,082
OUT!

143
00:07:27,901 --> 00:07:29,180
Mademoiselle.

144
00:07:29,237 --> 00:07:30,540
Thank you, monsieur.

145
00:07:30,575 --> 00:07:31,844
Farewell, mademoiselle.

146
00:07:32,584 --> 00:07:33,819
Be of good cheer.

147
00:07:34,482 --> 00:07:35,516
You are young.

148
00:07:35,670 --> 00:07:37,035
It's a fine day.

149
00:07:37,422 --> 00:07:39,272
And tomorrow
will be another.

150
00:07:42,082 --> 00:07:43,838
- Six handkerchiefs
at 80 francs.

151
00:07:43,873 --> 00:07:45,164
75.

152
00:07:46,759 --> 00:07:48,094
A good day to you, sir.

153
00:07:48,129 --> 00:07:49,196
Where's Marc?

154
00:07:49,458 --> 00:07:50,584
He went in there a minute.

155
00:07:52,523 --> 00:07:54,356
Here's your wine.
Pay you tomorrow.

156
00:08:17,812 --> 00:08:18,551
- What's that?

157
00:08:19,555 --> 00:08:20,587
- She lost her job.

158
00:08:20,706 --> 00:08:23,168
- No money, no family,
no place to go.

159
00:08:23,245 --> 00:08:24,842
- She seems to be
going with you.

160
00:08:25,119 --> 00:08:26,144
- Oh, no.

161
00:08:27,522 --> 00:08:28,897
Where are you going?

162
00:08:28,932 --> 00:08:30,272
- Uh, what, monsieur?

163
00:08:30,580 --> 00:08:31,535
- Where do you live?

164
00:08:31,570 --> 00:08:34,017
- Uh...uh...where do you live?

165
00:08:34,224 --> 00:08:35,923
- Ha.
Where do we live?

166
00:08:35,958 --> 00:08:36,690
- Everywhere.

167
00:08:36,875 --> 00:08:38,216
Last week, Marseilles.

168
00:08:38,251 --> 00:08:39,558
The week before, Avignon.

169
00:08:39,858 --> 00:08:41,284
Next week, Aix-les-Bains.

170
00:08:41,319 --> 00:08:42,712
- Huh.
You...you travel.

171
00:08:42,747 --> 00:08:43,976
How pleasant.

172
00:08:44,011 --> 00:08:45,930
- Who is she?
Where did you find her?

173
00:08:46,344 --> 00:08:47,052
- She loves me.

174
00:08:47,625 --> 00:08:48,941
- What's your name?

175
00:08:48,976 --> 00:08:50,223
- Lilette Daurier.

176
00:08:50,258 --> 00:08:52,701
But my father always
called me Lili.

177
00:08:52,801 --> 00:08:54,594
- Let me give you
a word of advice, Lili.

178
00:08:54,916 --> 00:08:56,616
Find someone else to love.

179
00:08:56,955 --> 00:08:58,325
This Marc is dangerous.

180
00:08:58,667 --> 00:09:01,608
He's got an assistant
with long, red fingernails.

181
00:09:01,643 --> 00:09:03,709
Ha.
Such men are dangerous.

182
00:09:04,093 --> 00:09:06,782
- Hey, listen,
couldn't old Pierre Corvier

183
00:09:06,817 --> 00:09:07,970
give her a job with the girls?

184
00:09:08,005 --> 00:09:10,318
Paul, he likes you.
You could talk to him.

185
00:09:10,353 --> 00:09:11,971
- Look, this is
your little project.

186
00:09:12,006 --> 00:09:12,847
I don't like it.

187
00:09:13,107 --> 00:09:14,944
- I'm only being
a good samaritan.

188
00:09:14,979 --> 00:09:16,783
- I've heard it
called that before.

189
00:09:16,818 --> 00:09:18,231
Come on, Jacquot.

190
00:09:18,948 --> 00:09:19,858
- See you later.

191
00:09:20,650 --> 00:09:23,534
He...he's angry?
The lame one, I mean.

192
00:09:23,569 --> 00:09:24,708
He's always angry.

193
00:09:24,743 --> 00:09:26,007
Why?

194
00:09:26,042 --> 00:09:28,449
Ah, he's a disagreeable man.
He's an angry man,

195
00:09:28,484 --> 00:09:29,840
and he always keeps to himself.

196
00:09:29,875 --> 00:09:30,875
[ Scream ]

197
00:09:31,196 --> 00:09:32,618
- What's the matter?
- I saw the man die!

198
00:09:32,653 --> 00:09:33,503
The man is dead!

199
00:09:33,538 --> 00:09:34,747
No.

200
00:09:34,782 --> 00:09:37,203
They are acrobats
rehearsing for the carnival.

201
00:09:37,238 --> 00:09:38,682
It's nothing. Look.

202
00:09:39,123 --> 00:09:40,239
There.

203
00:09:40,432 --> 00:09:41,015
Oh.

204
00:09:41,050 --> 00:09:41,598
See?

205
00:09:42,104 --> 00:09:43,166
Come along, now.

206
00:09:43,496 --> 00:09:45,482
I'll show you.
You hold this, will you?

207
00:09:46,604 --> 00:09:47,298
Come on.

208
00:09:48,650 --> 00:09:49,343
Come on.

209
00:09:50,796 --> 00:09:52,956
[ Hammering ]

210
00:09:58,299 --> 00:10:02,165
[ Music plays ]

211
00:10:08,365 --> 00:10:11,011
[ Marc whistling
to the music ]

212
00:10:18,810 --> 00:10:22,576
[ Marc continues whistling ]

213
00:10:43,438 --> 00:10:44,331
[ Dog barks ]

214
00:10:47,345 --> 00:10:48,553
My chateau.

215
00:10:56,923 --> 00:10:58,856
[ Closes door ]

216
00:11:11,818 --> 00:11:12,541
Blow.

217
00:11:15,310 --> 00:11:16,132
[ Lili gasps ]

218
00:11:16,974 --> 00:11:19,286
Now, what can we do
about you? Hmm?

219
00:11:19,711 --> 00:11:20,809
What would you like most?

220
00:11:20,844 --> 00:11:22,895
A glass of wine?
Something to eat?

221
00:11:22,990 --> 00:11:26,129
I...I would like most
to stay with you.

222
00:11:26,624 --> 00:11:28,051
I...I can cook.

223
00:11:28,316 --> 00:11:31,603
I...I could clean the house..
wash the dishes.

224
00:11:32,941 --> 00:11:33,885
Please.

225
00:11:39,935 --> 00:11:40,997
Kiss me.

226
00:11:41,817 --> 00:11:43,511
[ Lily kisses him ]

227
00:11:45,179 --> 00:11:47,106
You've never kissed a man before!

228
00:11:47,167 --> 00:11:48,431
Yes, many.

229
00:11:48,558 --> 00:11:49,499
That's a lie.

230
00:11:50,767 --> 00:11:51,615
Yes.

231
00:11:53,633 --> 00:11:55,059
How old are you, Lili?

232
00:11:55,284 --> 00:11:56,321
16.

233
00:11:59,141 --> 00:12:01,421
A girl of 16 should
have a little sense.

234
00:12:02,859 --> 00:12:05,022
Following people
in the streets.

235
00:12:06,808 --> 00:12:08,072
How did you get here?

236
00:12:08,572 --> 00:12:09,507
Well, I...

237
00:12:09,542 --> 00:12:13,016
I..I used to live in Manasse
with my father, you see?

238
00:12:13,051 --> 00:12:18,274
But then a month ago my father died,
so I came here to work with M. Godet,

239
00:12:18,309 --> 00:12:19,713
the baker, you know?

240
00:12:20,622 --> 00:12:22,930
But monsieur Godet
the baker was dead.

241
00:12:23,447 --> 00:12:25,469
So I couldn't work with him
in his bakery.

242
00:12:27,576 --> 00:12:28,658
That's all.

243
00:12:31,406 --> 00:12:34,140
You haven't had too good
a time with life, have you?

244
00:12:34,278 --> 00:12:37,350
Oh, things were nice
when I lived with my father.

245
00:12:37,771 --> 00:12:40,427
He...he would make me laugh.

246
00:12:40,722 --> 00:12:42,626
He'd tell me jokes.

247
00:12:43,778 --> 00:12:45,038
Shall I tell you a joke?

248
00:12:45,073 --> 00:12:45,886
Yes.

249
00:12:47,780 --> 00:12:50,630
When is a singer not a singer?

250
00:12:51,267 --> 00:12:52,424
When?

251
00:12:52,933 --> 00:12:54,545
When he's a little hoarse.

252
00:12:54,897 --> 00:12:55,818
Good, eh?

253
00:12:56,585 --> 00:12:57,468
Yeah.

254
00:12:58,926 --> 00:13:01,354
He was a watchmaker,
my father. You know that?

255
00:13:01,834 --> 00:13:03,459
He could fix any watch.

256
00:13:04,772 --> 00:13:07,497
Oh, shall I show you
my father's own watch?

257
00:13:08,031 --> 00:13:10,162
He let me keep it
when everything was sold.

258
00:13:10,465 --> 00:13:12,071
Keeps a very good time.

259
00:13:13,199 --> 00:13:15,513
Only sometimes I forget to wind it.

260
00:13:17,603 --> 00:13:18,886
It's gold-plated.

261
00:13:19,772 --> 00:13:20,548
Yes.

262
00:13:21,262 --> 00:13:22,767
Yes, it's very nice.

263
00:13:22,802 --> 00:13:24,273
Now, uh, look, Lili...

264
00:13:25,717 --> 00:13:27,994
Maybe I could get you
a job in the carnival.

265
00:13:28,950 --> 00:13:30,964
Well, what kind of job?

266
00:13:30,999 --> 00:13:32,978
Well, uh...can you dance?

267
00:13:33,710 --> 00:13:34,581
No.

268
00:13:34,972 --> 00:13:35,852
Uh...sing?

269
00:13:36,467 --> 00:13:39,030
Well, I...I can carry a tune, but...

270
00:13:39,561 --> 00:13:40,672
What can you do?

271
00:13:40,884 --> 00:13:42,850
I kept house for my father, you see.

272
00:13:42,868 --> 00:13:45,252
I have an assistant
who keeps house for me.

273
00:13:45,323 --> 00:13:47,883
Now, I want you to get yourself
something to eat,

274
00:13:48,392 --> 00:13:50,903
and I'll go and see what I can do
for you with Mr. Corvier.

275
00:13:51,143 --> 00:13:51,557
Oh!

276
00:13:51,592 --> 00:13:53,126
Don't do that.

277
00:13:54,201 --> 00:13:56,764
You mustn't throw yourself at men
that way. It isn't nice.

278
00:13:56,977 --> 00:13:59,878
Well, it's nice. I mean, it's nice,
but you shouldn't do it.

279
00:13:59,971 --> 00:14:00,710
I'll be back.

280
00:14:02,419 --> 00:14:03,403
Whew.

281
00:14:04,896 --> 00:14:08,080
[ Hammering sound ]

282
00:14:14,687 --> 00:14:16,112
Have you seen old Corvier?

283
00:14:16,428 --> 00:14:17,291
They're setting up.

284
00:14:17,359 --> 00:14:18,097
Oh.

285
00:14:19,881 --> 00:14:21,467
What are you going
to do about that girl?

286
00:14:24,076 --> 00:14:25,396
She's very young.

287
00:14:25,431 --> 00:14:26,716
She'll get older.

288
00:14:28,013 --> 00:14:29,241
Before her time.

289
00:14:30,015 --> 00:14:32,376
The female soul is like a chestnut.

290
00:14:33,177 --> 00:14:35,575
It must go through fire
before it becomes delicious.

291
00:14:35,610 --> 00:14:36,960
Very clever.

292
00:14:38,119 --> 00:14:39,437
How's Rosalie?

293
00:14:45,612 --> 00:14:47,366
I could learn to dislike him.

294
00:14:49,133 --> 00:14:50,505
I already have.

295
00:14:54,073 --> 00:14:55,353
She needs the job.

296
00:14:55,937 --> 00:14:57,613
I could use another waitress.

297
00:14:57,648 --> 00:14:58,122
Fine.

298
00:14:58,157 --> 00:14:59,180
Good figure?

299
00:15:00,525 --> 00:15:02,367
Just take her on for a while.

300
00:15:02,402 --> 00:15:04,318
You don't have to
keep her, you understand?

301
00:15:04,353 --> 00:15:06,357
I understand very well.

302
00:15:06,610 --> 00:15:08,195
Take her off your hands.

303
00:15:10,350 --> 00:15:11,493
Fine. Thanks.

304
00:15:12,035 --> 00:15:12,991
Thanks a lot.

305
00:15:14,412 --> 00:15:17,591
[ Organ musie ]

306
00:15:34,368 --> 00:15:39,426
[ Calliope plays
carnival music ]

307
00:16:12,194 --> 00:16:15,401
[ Cheers and applause ]

308
00:16:35,765 --> 00:16:40,596
[ Middle Eastern music plays ]

309
00:18:08,226 --> 00:18:11,136
[ Applause ]

310
00:18:15,347 --> 00:18:20,347
Ladies and gentlemen, we present
for your enjoyment now,

311
00:18:20,448 --> 00:18:25,265
that master of mystery,
Marcus the magnificent.

312
00:18:25,300 --> 00:18:27,440
[ Applause ]
[ Drumroll ]

313
00:18:55,067 --> 00:18:57,233
[ Applause ]

314
00:19:05,868 --> 00:19:07,745
[ Applause ]

315
00:19:57,593 --> 00:20:00,698
[ Applause ]

316
00:20:22,593 --> 00:20:25,499
[ Laughter ]

317
00:20:36,230 --> 00:20:37,457
Hup.

318
00:21:40,704 --> 00:21:41,609
Hup.

319
00:21:41,644 --> 00:21:43,613
[ Laughter ]

320
00:21:44,875 --> 00:21:45,706
Hup.

321
00:21:48,203 --> 00:21:49,197
Hup.

322
00:21:50,274 --> 00:21:52,822
No, please, no.

323
00:21:54,363 --> 00:21:54,944
Hup.

324
00:21:54,979 --> 00:21:55,525
No.

325
00:21:55,649 --> 00:21:56,389
[ Gasps ]

326
00:21:56,682 --> 00:21:57,736
No. No.

327
00:21:58,374 --> 00:21:59,713
[ Gasps ]

328
00:21:59,773 --> 00:22:00,613
Hup.

329
00:22:00,648 --> 00:22:04,185
[ Finale music plays ]

330
00:22:35,199 --> 00:22:38,863
[ Women talking ]

331
00:22:44,179 --> 00:22:45,309
Ha ha ha ha.

332
00:22:45,344 --> 00:22:46,170
Oh.

333
00:22:51,872 --> 00:22:52,551
Monsieur Marc, I...

334
00:22:52,586 --> 00:22:53,058
Hello.

335
00:22:53,093 --> 00:22:55,616
I...I saw you do the trick.

336
00:22:55,651 --> 00:22:56,162
Yeah?

337
00:22:56,197 --> 00:22:58,789
It was...beautiful.

338
00:22:58,824 --> 00:23:00,288
Well, thank you.
Thank you very much.

339
00:23:00,542 --> 00:23:02,322
But aren't you working?

340
00:23:03,296 --> 00:23:04,058
No more.

341
00:23:04,093 --> 00:23:05,060
Oh.

342
00:23:05,245 --> 00:23:06,673
Well...um...here.

343
00:23:06,708 --> 00:23:07,983
Have some fun at the carnival.

344
00:23:08,018 --> 00:23:10,886
Oh, thank you,
but Monsieur Corvier paid me.

345
00:23:10,921 --> 00:23:12,422
Oh, well, that's fine, then.

346
00:23:12,457 --> 00:23:13,537
- Come on. Let's eat.

347
00:23:13,769 --> 00:23:14,480
In a minute.

348
00:23:14,857 --> 00:23:16,707
Wh-wh-what shall I do now?

349
00:23:17,586 --> 00:23:20,522
Well, uh...why don't you go
back to that shop?

350
00:23:20,557 --> 00:23:22,776
That was a pretty good job you had.

351
00:23:23,514 --> 00:23:24,167
Job?

352
00:23:24,202 --> 00:23:26,345
Yeah. That fellow wasn't so bad.
He meant well.

353
00:23:26,949 --> 00:23:28,253
He was very jolly.

354
00:23:28,417 --> 00:23:30,094
That's the kind of job
you should have.

355
00:23:30,103 --> 00:23:33,265
Oh, but I...I...I want
to stay near you.

356
00:23:33,300 --> 00:23:33,998
You cannot.

357
00:23:34,198 --> 00:23:36,619
You don't want to make
trouble for me, do you?

358
00:23:36,976 --> 00:23:37,891
Oh...

359
00:23:37,926 --> 00:23:39,598
I-I'd rather die.

360
00:23:39,819 --> 00:23:40,489
Good girl.

361
00:23:40,789 --> 00:23:41,619
Well, good luck.

362
00:23:41,654 --> 00:23:42,415
[ Dogs barking ]

363
00:23:42,450 --> 00:23:43,888
But, Monsieur Marc...

364
00:23:44,046 --> 00:23:46,174
Must be rushing along now.
Talk to you later.

365
00:23:46,209 --> 00:23:48,221
[ Women talking ]

366
00:24:28,204 --> 00:24:30,116
[ Man ]  Hey, look what
we have here, John.

367
00:24:30,303 --> 00:24:31,623
[ Other man ]   Sorry.
You'll have to get out.

368
00:24:31,658 --> 00:24:34,097
The carnival's closed for the night.

369
00:24:34,132 --> 00:24:36,536
Hi. Hey, why don't you
go back home?

370
00:24:36,979 --> 00:24:38,527
Let's go. Let's go.
And hurry.

371
00:26:05,372 --> 00:26:06,483
[ Voice ]
- Hey.

372
00:26:06,651 --> 00:26:07,536
- [ Whistles ]

373
00:26:07,899 --> 00:26:08,591
- Lili.

374
00:26:09,922 --> 00:26:11,176
- Hey, Lili.

375
00:26:11,918 --> 00:26:12,799
- [ Whistles ]

376
00:26:14,442 --> 00:26:15,278
- Lili.

377
00:26:16,547 --> 00:26:17,313
- Yoo-hoo.

378
00:26:17,348 --> 00:26:20,365
Yes, it's me,
Carrot Top. Come over here.

379
00:26:21,027 --> 00:26:21,860
- Lili.

380
00:26:22,793 --> 00:26:23,873
- Come on down.

381
00:26:24,915 --> 00:26:26,026
- Come on down.

382
00:26:26,623 --> 00:26:28,887
- I have all sorts of things
to discuss with you,

383
00:26:28,922 --> 00:26:30,048
- and they can't wait.

384
00:26:30,635 --> 00:26:32,513
I can't imagine what
you're doing over there,

385
00:26:32,548 --> 00:26:33,656
but I wish you'd stop it.

386
00:26:34,093 --> 00:26:35,520
It'll have to wait until later.

387
00:26:35,919 --> 00:26:37,617
- This is much more important.

388
00:26:38,743 --> 00:26:42,209
- Come along now.
It's nicer over here.

389
00:26:42,325 --> 00:26:43,427
- Much nicer.

390
00:26:43,864 --> 00:26:47,093
And I'm a very interesting fellow.

391
00:26:47,305 --> 00:26:48,378
- Don't forget your purse.

392
00:26:49,066 --> 00:26:50,390
- Pick it up, Lili dear.

393
00:26:53,568 --> 00:26:55,005
- [ Humming ]

394
00:26:55,040 --> 00:26:57,067
- La la la la la la la la

395
00:26:57,365 --> 00:26:59,518
- Leave the suitcase.
You can get it later.

396
00:26:59,995 --> 00:27:02,538
Now hurry. Walk over here.

397
00:27:02,995 --> 00:27:04,911
- Right foot. Left foot.

398
00:27:05,107 --> 00:27:07,334
- Faster, please.
I'm frightfully impatient.

399
00:27:08,003 --> 00:27:08,958
Come along now.

400
00:27:10,113 --> 00:27:11,883
Well, come on. Come on.

401
00:27:12,570 --> 00:27:13,361
Closer.

402
00:27:15,171 --> 00:27:17,227
Well, now then.

403
00:27:18,007 --> 00:27:19,327
How ya been, Lili?

404
00:27:19,452 --> 00:27:21,134
Lose your job
over at the cabaret?

405
00:27:21,903 --> 00:27:22,826
Forget it.

406
00:27:23,203 --> 00:27:24,539
Let me see your locket.

407
00:27:25,638 --> 00:27:27,712
Ah, it's a watch.

408
00:27:27,871 --> 00:27:29,009
Does it run?

409
00:27:29,970 --> 00:27:31,037
Well, let me hear.

410
00:27:35,814 --> 00:27:37,645
Mmm, my.

411
00:27:37,680 --> 00:27:39,476
Very fine.

412
00:27:41,058 --> 00:27:42,152
Grr!

413
00:27:42,745 --> 00:27:43,888
- Do I frighten ya?

414
00:27:43,927 --> 00:27:45,265
Grr!

415
00:27:45,300 --> 00:27:47,538
- Oh, be quiet.
You don't frighten anybody.

416
00:27:47,743 --> 00:27:49,200
Well, I try.

417
00:27:50,330 --> 00:27:52,936
You must admit I try.

418
00:27:53,670 --> 00:27:54,933
Shake hands with Lili.

419
00:27:55,302 --> 00:27:57,995
I call her...Lili dear.

420
00:27:58,227 --> 00:27:59,325
Golo the Giant.

421
00:28:00,492 --> 00:28:04,988
Oh, my. I'm always so brave
until they get close to me.

422
00:28:05,135 --> 00:28:06,590
Girls frighten him.

423
00:28:06,966 --> 00:28:09,927
It's because I like them so.

424
00:28:09,962 --> 00:28:12,888
Ho ho ho ho ho
ho ho ho ho ho.

425
00:28:13,953 --> 00:28:16,190
He'll be all right when
he gets to know you better.

426
00:28:18,195 --> 00:28:20,746
Well, hello, baby.

427
00:28:21,758 --> 00:28:23,908
Go away, Reynardo.
I saw her first.

428
00:28:24,123 --> 00:28:26,221
Be careful.
He'll steal your watch.

429
00:28:26,443 --> 00:28:27,240
Go away.

430
00:28:27,611 --> 00:28:28,929
Not a chance.

431
00:28:29,311 --> 00:28:30,327
Let's ignore him.

432
00:28:30,348 --> 00:28:31,614
Maybe he'll go away.

433
00:28:31,649 --> 00:28:34,362
[ Humming ]

434
00:28:34,412 --> 00:28:37,279
He's jealous of me
because I'm cleverer than he is,

435
00:28:37,314 --> 00:28:40,148
and ever so much more
handsome, don't you think?

436
00:28:40,426 --> 00:28:41,829
No, she don't.

437
00:28:41,830 --> 00:28:44,768
I think my eyes
are my best feature.

438
00:28:45,188 --> 00:28:48,603
Come a little closer
and look into them.

439
00:28:49,406 --> 00:28:50,748
Ahh.

440
00:28:51,293 --> 00:28:52,736
I'll tell Marguerite.

441
00:28:53,070 --> 00:28:57,583
Tell me, do you
like champagne, hmm?

442
00:28:57,618 --> 00:28:58,891
Wait till Marguerite sees this.

443
00:28:59,055 --> 00:28:59,658
- Marguerite.

444
00:28:59,693 --> 00:29:01,433
May I have the next waltz?

445
00:29:01,468 --> 00:29:03,174
Reynardo, behave yourself.

446
00:29:03,360 --> 00:29:03,949
Uh-oh.

447
00:29:03,984 --> 00:29:06,563
Don't listen to him,
my dear. He is a seducer.

448
00:29:06,598 --> 00:29:08,421
With a heart like a kitten.

449
00:29:08,456 --> 00:29:09,064
Ho!

450
00:29:09,177 --> 00:29:11,698
I don't know why
nobody trusts me.

451
00:29:11,733 --> 00:29:13,015
I know why.

452
00:29:13,302 --> 00:29:15,412
Well, keep it to yourself,
you old hag.

453
00:29:15,447 --> 00:29:17,226
WHAT did you say?

454
00:29:17,584 --> 00:29:19,555
- Uh...what did you hear?

455
00:29:19,590 --> 00:29:21,339
- Reynardo, I must insist
that you address me

456
00:29:21,374 --> 00:29:22,392
- more respectfully.

457
00:29:22,524 --> 00:29:23,577
Introduce us.

458
00:29:23,701 --> 00:29:25,503
Introduce us?
Introduce us?

459
00:29:25,538 --> 00:29:28,233
She has to be introduced to a girl,
but, believe me, when it's a man, she...

460
00:29:28,268 --> 00:29:31,038
Reynardo, introduce us.

461
00:29:31,511 --> 00:29:33,906
Lili, Marguerite.

462
00:29:34,377 --> 00:29:35,403
How do you do, Lili?

463
00:29:35,766 --> 00:29:37,082
How do you do?

464
00:29:37,117 --> 00:29:38,547
He's a dreadful wolf.

465
00:29:40,025 --> 00:29:42,254
I thought he was a fox.

466
00:29:42,289 --> 00:29:44,656
Ha! That's the worst
kind of wolf.

467
00:29:45,189 --> 00:29:47,876
And as for you,
I know your kind.

468
00:29:48,055 --> 00:29:49,877
So innocent.

469
00:29:49,957 --> 00:29:51,876
Ha ha. Oh, yes,
so innocent.

470
00:29:52,936 --> 00:29:55,700
But making goo-goo eyes
at Reynardo. Really!

471
00:29:56,979 --> 00:29:59,056
- Oh, my. What'd you
do to Marguerite?

472
00:29:59,091 --> 00:30:01,134
What'd you say to her?
She's disturbed.

473
00:30:01,169 --> 00:30:02,598
I...I didn't say anything.

474
00:30:02,633 --> 00:30:04,028
Well, you'd better make it up.

475
00:30:04,063 --> 00:30:05,414
Be nice to her.

476
00:30:05,803 --> 00:30:06,851
How?

477
00:30:07,160 --> 00:30:09,888
Hmm. Well, let's see, now...

478
00:30:10,374 --> 00:30:11,400
I've got it.

479
00:30:11,633 --> 00:30:12,554
Flatter her.

480
00:30:12,849 --> 00:30:13,470
What?

481
00:30:13,505 --> 00:30:14,639
Flatter her.

482
00:30:14,674 --> 00:30:15,767
Say she's pretty.

483
00:30:15,802 --> 00:30:17,729
Oh, Marguerite's very pretty.

484
00:30:18,145 --> 00:30:19,353
Louder.

485
00:30:19,418 --> 00:30:20,338
I'll do it.

486
00:30:20,784 --> 00:30:23,298
Marguerite is very pretty.

487
00:30:23,333 --> 00:30:25,814
She has a face
like a mountain goat.

488
00:30:25,849 --> 00:30:27,130
- [ Gasps ]

489
00:30:27,228 --> 00:30:28,852
- And she's witty.

490
00:30:29,006 --> 00:30:31,232
- She has the brains
of an angleworm.

491
00:30:31,422 --> 00:30:32,765
[ Marguerite ]
- I heard that, Reynardo.

492
00:30:33,131 --> 00:30:33,872
Uh-oh.

493
00:30:33,956 --> 00:30:34,865
I heard what you said, Reynardo.

494
00:30:34,900 --> 00:30:37,813
You're a wicked, insulting no-good,
and I'll have nothing more to do with you.

495
00:30:37,848 --> 00:30:39,553
She's very upset now.

496
00:30:39,926 --> 00:30:42,876
Be nice to her.
Ask her to dance for us.

497
00:30:42,992 --> 00:30:46,605
Uh...uh...will you dance
for us, Marguerite?

498
00:30:46,640 --> 00:30:47,359
What?

499
00:30:47,637 --> 00:30:49,711
Ah. Ah. Ha ha ha.

500
00:30:49,836 --> 00:30:50,886
Well, thank you.

501
00:30:50,921 --> 00:30:53,734
- I don't have my ballet slippers,
but I'll try.

502
00:30:53,769 --> 00:30:55,090
- Sing something, my dear.

503
00:30:55,124 --> 00:30:55,998
- Anything, you know?

504
00:30:56,033 --> 00:30:56,830
Oh, well, I...

505
00:30:56,865 --> 00:30:57,627
Any old thing.

506
00:30:59,955 --> 00:31:02,669
Oh. I remember
hi-Lili, hi-lo.

507
00:31:02,704 --> 00:31:03,191
Sweet?

508
00:31:03,226 --> 00:31:04,821
It's just an old song, but..

509
00:31:05,127 --> 00:31:07,203
I used to sing it with my father.

510
00:31:07,238 --> 00:31:08,116
It'll do.

511
00:31:08,268 --> 00:31:11,276
'On every tree,
there sits a bird.'

512
00:31:11,311 --> 00:31:14,170
[ Accordian starts to play ]

513
00:31:14,368 --> 00:31:15,578
Come on.
You know it.

514
00:31:16,193 --> 00:31:17,409
Come on.
Let's hear it.

515
00:31:18,560 --> 00:31:24,244
<i>On every tree there sits a bird
singing a song of love.</i>

516
00:31:24,474 --> 00:31:27,557
<i>On every tree there sits a bird,</i>

517
00:31:27,592 --> 00:31:35,046
<i>and every one I ever heard
could break my heart without a word.</i>

518
00:31:35,081 --> 00:31:39,668
<i>Singing a song of love</i>

519
00:31:39,871 --> 00:31:40,574
Ahem.

520
00:31:41,679 --> 00:31:48,913
<i>A song of love is a sad song.
hi-Lili, hi-Lili, hi-lo.</i>

521
00:31:49,070 --> 00:31:52,817
<i>A song of love is a song of woe.</i>

522
00:31:52,852 --> 00:31:56,139
<i>Don't ask me how I know.</i>

523
00:31:56,386 --> 00:31:59,734
<i>A song of love is a sad song,</i>

524
00:31:59,769 --> 00:32:03,495
<i>for I have loved,
and it's so.</i>

525
